consent:
The only requirement for participation in this study is that you are an adult (18 years or older). 

 

Purpose: 

The purpose of this research study is to test interview techniques for use when questioning criminal suspects or intelligence sources.

 

Procedures:  

If you volunteer to participate in this research study, we will ask you to do the following:

 

You will be asked to take part in an online study where you will be watch video clips. You will be asked to imagine that you are the first person in the video that’s performing several activities. After these watching the clips, you will be interviewed. You may be asked to lie during this interview. After the interview, you will be asked to complete questionnaires about your experiences in the study.

 

The interview will be recorded. You will be given an opportunity to listen to this recording, and you will be given the opportunity to delete the file. If you withdraw from the study, we will delete your recording. All recordings will be stored in a locked data storage room or password protected hard drive. Only members of the research team will have access to the recordings. Recordings will be used only for research purposes (e.g., data coding).

 

We cannot tell you every detail of this study ahead of time, but if you are willing to participate under these conditions we will explain the procedures to you fully after your participation.

 

 

Time Commitment:

Your participation in this research study is expected to last for a total of 60 minutes.

 

Potential Risks or Discomforts: 

 
Participants may experience some stress during the interview.  

 
 

Potential Benefits: 
 

 
You will not directly benefit from your participation in this research study.

 
This study may provide valuable information about how police and military personnel can question suspects in an effective manner.

 
 

Payment for Participation: 
 

 

You will be paid £7.75 for your participation.
 

 
 

Confidentiality: 
 

We will make our best efforts to maintain confidentiality of any information that is collected during this research study. We will disclose this information only with your permission or as required by law.

 

We will protect your confidentiality by ensuring that your name and other identifying information is not be present on any of the questionnaires for this study. All documents and recordings will be stored in a locked data storage room or on a password protected hard drive (for electronic files).

 

The research team, authorized University staff and government agencies that oversee this type of research may have access to research data and records in order to monitor the research. Research records provided to authorized, non-University individuals will not contain identifiable information about you. Publications and/or presentations that result from this study will not identify you by name.
 

 
 

Participants’ Rights: 
 

 
Your participation in this research study is entirely voluntary. If you decide not to participate, there will be no penalty to you, and you will not lose any benefits to which you are otherwise entitled.

 
You can decide to withdraw your consent and stop participating in the research at any time, without any penalty.



 

Contact:

Lina Nyström

PhD Candidate

lina.nystrom@psy.gu.se

strategy_free: I came up with a perfect, coherent story about the innocent guy in my friend's room.

My strategy was to come up with a scenario that I was thinking of applying for a job in the company, and before doing so I wanted to check the premises and get a feeling of the working environment. I would tell them that I learned about open positions from a friend that has an acquaintance in the company (whom I didn't know). That way I could leave this vague and wouldn't have to say that I directly know someone who works at the company.
change_strategy_free: I didn't change my strategy and tried to stick to it regardless of the questions asked.

strategy_free: My strategy was to give a motivation for why I was in the building in the first place and give an account that matched up with my activity halfway through, I completely omitted the rest (installing spyware, placing the bug). I said that the phone i picked up in room 540 on the 5th floor was a phone I had left by mistake, and then I was gonna be on my way out but a supposed colleague of mine texted me to wait for them, so I waited in the basement; after that I was supposed to be on my way out but I was stopped by the security guard.

At first, I did not want to give the interviewer many details about my whereabouts in the building. A great deal of information is the cause of many questions. But he informed me that there are cameras in the building. So, I admitted to being in places where there were cameras and I made up stories to justify my presence in these places. These stories were not very complex, in order not to raise many questions. On the contrary, I believe that they were short and believable. All in all, I believe that I made a good impression on the interviewer.
change_strategy_free: Yes, I changed strategy, because he informed me that there were cameras in the building. So, I could not deny being in a certain place. So, I had to make up believable stories to convince him why I was present at that time.

strategy_free: I wanted to ensure I had no link to any big corporation and made sure It was clear that my technology knowledge was limited. I wanted to distance myself from any relation to the business I committed my crime in. I wanted to make sure that I had a reason for looking around a location trying to find my friend in case i had been seen on any cameras whilst carrying out my mission.
give little information so i could not contradict myself. make myself seem as oblivious and naive as possible.

strategy_free: I tried to keep the same story throughout and I looked them in the eye. I was also quite nervous and kept fidgeting with my hands where they could not see, in order to keep myself calm

strategy_free: I tried to provide a decent alibi at the start without providing any incriminating evidence or anything that could be used to catch me out. However, considering I was walking around an office building with leather gloves there probably wasn't too much I could do
change_strategy_free: I provided shorter answers when it became clear all my movements were logged on CCTV

strategy_free:
At first I tried to force an amount of time pressure by stating that I had a doctor's appointment to attend. This was to try and force them to rush through their questions and to not dwell on any of my answers for too long at a time. I brought this up again later while the interview was looking through their notes to try and create urgency and not allow them additional time to think.

I didn't want to lie completely to the interviewer as if they had concrete evidence that I had taken a particular action or been in a certain area they might have been able to catch me in a lie. I tried to give a little bit of truth in terms of certain areas that I had been, the basement, the balcony, the 5th floor, and tried to create a reasonable excuse for why I had been there. I also tried to remain vague and hazy in my memory about specific details so that if a line of questioning was followed up on I would be able to feign confusion or claim I had made a mistake.

I denied knowledge of technology and politics when asked, I felt this could be risky as it might raise suspicion slightly but alternatively, admitting to this could immediately put the interview into a guilty mindframe.

I promised to make myself available over the next few days and offered details that would take time to check, knowing that I would not be returning and that although my story may not hold up on further inspection, I may be believed to be innocent in the moment and so I would not be held immediately for further interrogation.
change_strategy_free: When the interviewer seemed to be sceptical I tried to be even more friendly, appear even more "open and honest" , and take a bit more time over some answers to make it seem as if I was genuinely having to recollect something that didn't stand out as important in my mind.

strategy_free: I resorted to acting like an agent of the law, who was there to enforce policy and regulation as opposed to someone who was up to commit acts of crime

I told the interviewer that I was only in the building because my friend had asked me to bring medication for her at work, I went there and as soon as i was about to leave, that is when i was asked not to leave and told that there is a case being investigated.
Give detail that was vague, but hard to counter, as the goal was to get out the building.
